{
  "local_port": 48000,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What IDE do you use for C/C++?",
  "response": "I don't use software, but I can certainly recommend some popular Integrated Development Environments (IDEs) that are widely used for C and C++ development. Here are a few options you might consider:\n\n1. **Visual Studio**\n   - **Platform:** Windows\n   - **Features:** \n     - Comprehensive debugging and testing tools\n     - IntelliSense for smart code completion\n     - Integrated version control\n     - Extensive extension ecosystem\n   - **Pros:** Highly robust with excellent support for large projects, especially on Windows.\n\n2. **CLion**\n   - **Platform:** Windows, macOS, Linux\n   - **Features:**\n     - Smart code analysis and refactoring\n     - Integrated debugger and support for CMake\n     - Seamless integration with version control systems\n     - Supports remote development\n   - **Pros:** Developed by JetBrains, it's known for its intelligent coding assistance and cross-platform capabilities.\n\n3. **Eclipse CDT (C/C++ Development Tooling)**\n   - **Platform:** Windows, macOS, Linux\n   - **Features:**\n     - Code editor with syntax highlighting and code completion\n     - Debugging tools\n     - Project management\n     - Plugin support for additional functionalities\n   - **Pros:** Free and open-source with a large community and extensive customization options.\n\n4. **Code::Blocks**\n   - **Platform:** Windows, macOS, Linux\n   - **Features:**\n     - Customizable and extensible with plugins\n     - Support for multiple compilers (GCC, Clang, MSVC)\n     - Integrated debugger\n     - Project management tools\n   - **Pros:** Lightweight and straightforward, making it suitable for beginners and smaller projects.\n\n5. **Visual Studio Code (with Extensions)**\n   - **Platform:** Windows, macOS, Linux\n   - **Features:**\n     - Highly customizable through extensions\n     - Built-in terminal and Git integration\n     - Syntax highlighting and IntelliSense\n     - Debugging support with appropriate extensions\n   - **Pros:** While not a full-fledged IDE out of the box, its flexibility allows it to be tailored for C/C++ development effectively.\n\n6. **Xcode**\n   - **Platform:** macOS\n   - **Features:**\n     - Integrated debugger and testing tools\n     - Interface Builder for designing UI (primarily for Apple platforms)\n     - Version control integration\n     - Support for C, C++, Objective-C, and Swift\n   - **Pros:** Best suited for developers targeting Apple ecosystems.\n\n**Choosing the Right IDE:**\n- **Project Requirements:** Larger projects might benefit from the robust features of Visual Studio or CLion, while smaller projects could work well with Code::Blocks or Visual Studio Code.\n- **Operating System:** Ensure the IDE is compatible with your OS. For instance, Xcode is exclusive to macOS.\n- **Budget:** Some IDEs like CLion are commercial products, while others like Eclipse CDT and Code::Blocks are free.\n- **Performance:** Lightweight IDEs might be preferable if you're working on a system with limited resources.\n\nUltimately, the best IDE depends on your specific needs, preferences, and the nature of the projects you're working on. It might be beneficial to try a few different options to see which one aligns best with your workflow.",
